        <!-- SEO Content -->
        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How to Calculate a Tip</h2>
            <p>Calculating a <strong>tip</strong> is straightforward: multiply the bill amount by the tip percentage you want to leave. For example, on a $50 bill with a 20% tip, the calculation is $50 x 0.20 = $10 tip, making the total $60. This tip calculator automates that math and adds useful features like bill splitting, rounding, and pre-tax tipping.</p>
            <p>The standard tipping range in the United States is <strong>15–20%</strong> for most sit-down restaurant service, with 20% increasingly considered the baseline for good service. For exceptional service, 25% or more is appropriate. Tipping customs vary by service type — delivery drivers, salon professionals, and taxi drivers all have different expectations.</p>

            <h2>How Much to Tip: The Standard Percentages</h2>
            <p>The most common tip percentages and when to use them:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>15%</strong> — Adequate service; the traditional minimum for restaurant tipping</li>
                <li><strong>18%</strong> — Good service; a common default for groups and auto-gratuity</li>
                <li><strong>20%</strong> — Great service; the modern standard tip that most servers expect</li>
                <li><strong>25%+</strong> — Exceptional service, complex orders, or when you want to show extra appreciation</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Pre-Tax vs Post-Tax Tipping</h2>
            <p>Etiquette experts agree that you should calculate your tip on the <strong>pre-tax subtotal</strong>, not the total that includes sales tax. Since sales tax rates vary from 0% in states like Oregon and Montana to over 10% in some cities, tipping on the post-tax amount means you're effectively tipping on the government's cut. On a $100 meal with 10% sales tax, tipping 20% pre-tax saves you $2 compared to tipping on the $110 post-tax total.</p>

            <h2>Splitting the Bill</h2>
            <p>When dining with a group, the simplest approach is to <strong>split the total evenly</strong> — calculate the tip on the full bill, add it to the subtotal, and divide by the number of people. This calculator handles that automatically when you set the number of people above 1. For groups of 6 or more, many restaurants automatically add an 18–20% gratuity to the bill, so check your receipt before adding an additional tip.</p>

            <h2>When to Round Up</h2>
            <p>Rounding up your total to the nearest dollar is a simple way to slightly increase your tip while making the math cleaner. For example, if your bill is $43.50 and a 20% tip is $8.70 (total $52.20), rounding up to $53 increases the effective tip to $9.50 (about 21.8%). The round-up option in this calculator adjusts the tip amount to bring the total to the next whole dollar.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <div class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much should you tip at a restaurant?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">The standard tip at a restaurant in the United States is 15–20% of the pre-tax bill. For excellent service, 20–25% is customary. At fine dining establishments, 20% is generally the minimum. If you received poor service, 10–15% is still expected unless the experience was truly unacceptable. Always tip on the pre-tax subtotal, not the total that includes sales tax.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Should you tip on the pre-tax or post-tax amount?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Etiquette experts recommend tipping on the pre-tax subtotal, not the amount that includes sales tax. Sales tax rates vary by location (from 0% to over 10%), so tipping on the post-tax total means you'd effectively be tipping on the tax itself. However, many people tip on the total for simplicity — the difference is usually small on typical bills.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much do you tip for delivery?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">For food delivery, tip 15–20% of the order total, with a minimum of $3–5 for small orders. For large or complex orders, tip closer to 20%. If the weather is bad, the delivery is far, or the driver had to climb stairs, consider tipping more. For grocery delivery, 15–20% or $5 minimum is standard. Most delivery drivers rely heavily on tips for their income.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do you split a tip among a group?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">To split a tip evenly, calculate the total tip on the full bill, then divide by the number of people. For example, on a $120 bill with a 20% tip, the tip is $24, so each person in a group of 4 pays $6 in tip ($36 total per person including their share of the bill). Some groups prefer to have each person tip on their own items instead of splitting evenly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much should you tip a hairdresser or barber?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">The standard tip for a hairdresser, barber, or salon professional is 15–20% of the service cost. For exceptional service, coloring, or complex styling, 20–25% is appropriate. If multiple stylists work on your hair (e.g., a colorist and a stylist), tip each person separately. It's also customary to tip the shampoo person $3–5.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Do you tip on takeout orders?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Tipping on takeout is not traditionally required, but has become more common since 2020. A tip of 10–15% is a generous gesture for takeout, especially for large or complex orders. If the restaurant staff packaged your order carefully, included extras, or you're a regular customer, tipping shows appreciation. Many point-of-sale systems now prompt for tips on takeout.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between a tip and a gratuity?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">A tip and a gratuity are essentially the same thing — both refer to extra money given to a service worker beyond the bill amount. However, "gratuity" is sometimes used for mandatory charges added to the bill (e.g., 18% auto-gratuity for large parties), while "tip" usually implies a voluntary amount. Mandatory gratuities are common for groups of 6 or more at restaurants.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much should you tip a taxi or rideshare driver?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">For taxi drivers, tip 15–20% of the fare, with a minimum of $2–3 for short rides. For rideshare services like Uber and Lyft, 15–20% or $2–5 is standard. Tip more if the driver helped with luggage, navigated difficult traffic, or provided excellent service. For airport rides or long trips, 15–20% of the total fare is customary.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is it rude not to tip in the United States?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">In the United States, not tipping for table service at a restaurant is considered very rude, as servers typically earn a base wage of $2.13–$5.00 per hour and depend on tips for most of their income. For other services like delivery, salon visits, and taxis, tipping is strongly expected. The only situations where not tipping is acceptable are counter service, fast food, and self-service establishments.</div>
            </div>
        </div>

